 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uhalus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Halus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/14/01 9:57:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=148.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_supermad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Oh,please.</span><hr size=1> Morgrist...<br>
<br>
I am not questioning the powers of a shadowknight -- I have known many in my many past lives and have felt their deadly touch. It's the perceived source of these powers that I find laughable. <br>
<br>
Great powers lie within each of us, and all that you can hope to channel through a false diety is some bit of focus. This focus may help pull you concentrate and be strong, but be certain that it is still YOUR mind doing the concentrating. With proper training, you can achieve equal power by contemplating a perfect jewel, a sharp blade, a blade of grass, or, perhaps in your case, the stench of rotting corpses. (I say I have met and fought many shadowknights...I do not claim to understand their disgusting inspirations.)<br>
<br>
These gods you speak of live because of your belief in them. Cease your belief and you can be sure their powers will fade to nothingness and they will disappear like so many before them. Tune your belief in yourself and your powers will approach that of these gods you so willingly submit to.  <br>
<br>
My past lives and vivid dreams have also brought me to the Planes you speak of, and I have seen this god of yours and his army fall like so many Crushbone orcs. Sure, he put up a good fight, but if you think he's immortal, or even powerful compared to some of the other ancient creatures of Norrath, then you are a bigger fool than you would have us believe.<br>
<br>
Perhaps we shall meet on the battlefield one day and you can prove me wrong. Until then, give my regards to the foul, egotistical monkey you call a god. Tell him that although my progress is slow, it is steady, and one day I will take a trip to  his pathetic plane and bring home some souvenirs.<br>
<br>
Halus<br>
Agnostic Enchanter<br>
<br>
